            <strong>ðŸ‡¸ðŸ‡¾ EU members normalize relations with Syria:</strong> 
            French and German foreign ministers have kicked off 2025 by making <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-h4-10-official-visits" target="_blank">official visits</a> to Syria. Both countries want to restore relations with Syria and provide transitional justice for the suffering caused by the Assad regime. They agreed that lifting sanctions depends on the political process. However, German foreign minister Anna Baerboch stated that Europe would support Syria in the transition but <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-h4-11-would-not-finance" target="_blank">would not finance</a> new Islamist structures. She also said that women and minorities' role in the new government is conditional to relations with Germany and the EU.
          </p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4"> 
            <strong>ðŸ‡©ðŸ‡ª Musk gets reprimanded:</strong> 
            German Chancellor Olaf Scholz subtly criticized <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-h5-12-elon-musks-influence" target="_blank">Elon Muskâ€™s influence</a> on President-elect Trump, stating that Germanyâ€™s future would be shaped by "the vast majority of reasonable and decent people" rather than "the owners of social media." This comes amid allegations that Musk had attempted to interfere in Germany's upcoming elections by supporting the far-right party Alternative for Germany and calling for Scholz's resignation. <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-h5-13-german-politicians" target="_blank">German politicians</a> from other parties didn't take his remarks and endorsement too kindly. The German AFD leader Alice Weidel has been in touch with Elon Musk, and he will invite her for a live interview on Jan 10th on his platform X.
          </p>
          </mj-text>
