          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px;">Whatâ€™s going on in Moldova?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Moldova is arguably one of the countries most affected by the war in Ukraine, and people see it as next in line for <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-14-conflict-with-russia" target="_blank">conflict with Russia</a>. The country had a dramatic end to 2024, with election run-offs giving the incumbent pro-EU president Maia Sandu a <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-15-narrow-victory" target="_blank">narrow victory</a>. The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-16-eu-referendum" target="_blank">EU referendum</a> also passed by a small margin, primarily thanks to the Moldovan diaspora living and working abroad.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-17-parliamentary-elections" target="_blank">Parliamentary elections</a> will take place in Moldova in 2025. If the government of Prime Minister Dorin Recean, a Sandu ally, does not develop better social policies and more judicial and anti-corruption reforms, the country's pro-European path could be at risk. The pro-Russian contingent remains relatively high, particularly in areas such as <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-18-gagauzia" target="_blank">Gagauzia</a>, an autonomous region in southern Moldova.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">If Moldova hopes to realize its EU dreams, it must address its <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-19-situation-in-transnistria" target="_blank">situation in Transnistria</a>, which has remained at a stalemate since 1992. The separatist region and its status quo are valuable ways for Russia to keep Moldova from drifting more to the West. However, much of Russiaâ€™s focus has gone to Ukraine, which has put Transnistria on a lower footing. Despite asking for help earlier this year, they didnâ€™t get significant <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-20-assistance-from-russia" target="_blank">assistance from Russia</a>. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Transnistria also faces <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-21-demographic-problems" target="_blank">demographic problems</a>. Most of the population is elderly because most young people go to Moldova or Russia for better economic opportunities. Its weakened status could eventually lead to some dialogue with Moldova. Although <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-01-2025-bq1-22-reintegrating" target="_blank">reintegrating</a> Transnistria would present many challenges, so does allowing the status quo to continue. Currently, they are in a state of emergency over the Russian gas issue and are trying to mitigate this by seeking alternative energy sources.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
